'''Eben Matlis''' (August 28, 1923 - March 27, 2015) was a [[mathematician]] known for his contributions to the theory of [[ring (mathematics)|rings]] and [[module (mathematics)|modules]], especially for his work with [[injective module]]s over [[commutative ring|commutative]] [[Noetherian ring]]s, and his introduction of [[Matlis duality]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Eben Matlis |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/156848332/eben-matlis |publisher=Findagrave |accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>

Matlis earned his Ph.D. at the [[University of Chicago]] in 1958,<ref name=IAS/> with [[Irving Kaplansky]] as advisor. He is an emeritus professor at [[Northwestern University]]<ref>{{cite LAF|id=no2010056237}}</ref> and was a member of the [[Institute for Advanced Study]] from August 1962 to June 1963.<ref name=IAS>{{cite web |url=https://www.ias.edu/scholars/eben-matlis |title=Eben Matlis |publisher=Institute for Advanced Study}}</ref>

