'''Joseph J. Rotman''' (May 26, 1934 –  October 16, 2016<ref>[http://www.news-gazette.com/obituaries/2016-10-18/joseph-rotman.html Joseph Rotman (obituary)], [[The News-Gazette (Champaign-Urbana)|The News-Gazette]], Tuesday, October 18, 2016. </ref>) was a Professor of Mathematics at the [[University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.math.uiuc.edu/~rotman/ |title=J. Rotman |publisher=uiuc.edu |accessdate=August 6, 2016}}</ref> and also a published author of 10 textbooks.

Rotman was born in Chicago. He did his undergraduate and graduate work at the [[University of Chicago]], where he received his doctorate in 1959 with a thesis in abelian groups written under the direction of [[Irving Kaplansky]].<ref>{{MathGenealogy|822}}</ref> In 1959 he moved to the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign, where he spent the rest of his mathematical career. Rotman retired from UIUC in 2004.<ref name=MT /> His research interests lay in the area of algebra, involving [[abelian groups]], [[Module (mathematics)|modules]], [[homological algebra]], and [[combinatorics]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.math.uiuc.edu/~rotman/ |title=J. Rotman |publisher=uiuc.edu |accessdate=August 6, 2016}}</ref>

Rotman was the Managing Editor of the ''[[Proceedings of the American Mathematical Society]]'' in 1972-1973.<ref name=MT>[http://www.math.uiuc.edu/mathtimes/mathtimes_sp04.pdf Retirements: Joseph Rotman], Math Times, Spring 2004, p. 9, Department of Mathematics, [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]]. </ref> In 1985 he was the Annual Visiting Lecturer of the [[South African Mathematical Society]].<ref>[http://www.math.illinois.edu/People/facultyhonors.html Faculty honors], Department of Mathematics, [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]].</ref> 

A partial list of Rotman's publications includes:

* ''An Introduction to Homological Algebra'' (1979), Pure and Applied Mathematics, vol. 85, Academic Press; {{ISBN|0-12-599250-5}}
* ''An Introduction to Algebraic Topology'' (1988),  Springer-Verlag; {{ISBN|0-387-96678-1}}
* ''An Introduction to the Theory of Groups'' (1995),  Springer-Verlag; {{ISBN|0-387-94285-8}}
* ''A First Course in Abstract Algebra'' (2000), Prentice Hall; {{ISBN|0-13-011584-3}} 
* ''Advanced Modern Algebra'' (2002), Prentice Hall; {{ISBN|0-13-087868-5}}
* ''Journey into Mathematics: an introduction to proofs'' (2006), [[Dover Publications]]; {{ISBN|0-486-45306-5}}

